<div itemprop="articleBody">
<h2>Tutorial 8. Working on the Shape of the Train.</h2>
<p><strong>I start putting ruffles on the stiff train gore. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The ruffles are cut from tulle with a width of 3 meters. </strong>I fold the tulle in half to make them double, make a row of stitches, and gather it up. In other words, I take a double-layer piece of tulle with a length of 1.5m and gather it so as to match the length of the corresponding joint area.</p>
<p>You will need two 3-meter-long strips of tulle for each ruffle of<strong> the actual size skirt. </strong>The thicker your tulle is, the fewer ruffles you will need, and vice versa.</p>
<p><strong>I will show you the ruffles layout a little later </strong>because I want you to first listen to my arguments and understand the principle of making such layouts so you can make one yourself for a skirt of any style.</p>
<p><strong>I have cut four double-layer ruffles with a width of 17cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The first ruffle goes 2cm above the bottom edge of the stiff train gore. </strong></p>
<p><strong>Please note </strong>that you must leave seam allowances along the sides of the gore to join it with the rest of the skirt.</p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image003.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>The next 17cm-wide double-layer ruffle is placed 1cm from the first one. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Starting from the third ruffle, I start gradually straightening the rounded bottom edge of the gore. For this reason, </strong>there must be 3cm between the middle of the third 17cm-wide ruffle and the middle of the previous ruffle. Their ends are supposed to gradually come together at the sides of the gore.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image005.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The fourth 17cm-wide ruffle is placed at a 2cm interval from the third one in the middle. Their ends gradually come together at the sides of the gore.</strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image007.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>I have also prepared five ruffles with a width of 25cm. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The first three ruffles are put down at 2.5cm intervals in the middle </strong>and I gradually bring them down to 2cm as I approach the sides. This is how I compensate for the rounded bottom edge of the gore.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image009.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Next, I will make longer ruffles and start putting them on the train support. </strong>At the moment, we are working on the back of the skirt and the ruffles are only just starting to fall upon the floor forming a transition from the skirt to the floor. And then I will start making longer ruffles to fill in the triangular space between the skirt and the floor.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image011.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>Now I only need to put two 25cm-wide ruffles on the piece. </strong></p>
<p><strong>The ruffles now basically go along a straight horizontal line. The rest of the ruffles will go along a convex line, i.e. opposite to the half-circle bottom edge of the gore. </strong></p>
<p><strong>In order to achieve this effect, I put the next ruffle at a 5cm interval from the middle of the last ruffle and bring the interval down to 2cm at the sides. </strong>This kind of a layout is justified for our train because it helps the ruffles settle better in the desired direction.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image013.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The last 25cm-wide ruffle will be put at a 3cm interval from the middle of the previous ruffle and at 2cm intervals at the sides.</strong></p>
<p><strong>I put a 45cm-wide ruffle on the gore, again in a convex line. And I add another 27cm-wide ruffle to achieve a smooth transition from the skirt to the train support. </strong></p>
<p><strong><br>
<img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image015.jpg" alt=""></strong></p>
<p><strong>Next, I put down a 60cm-wide ruffle at a 4cm interval from the middle of the 27cm-wide ruffle and at 3cm intervals at the sides. There is 14cm left before the middle of the top ruffle guideline. </strong>Please remember to multiply all these intervals by two when working on the actual size skirt.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image017.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I use a 27cm-wide ruffle to improve the transition from the skirt to the train. </strong>The guidelines become shorter and the ruffles thicker as you approach the waistline, which helps create a smoother transition to the train.</p>
<p><strong>I divide in half the distance between the middle of the 60cm-wide ruffle and the middle of the top edge and put down a 27cm-wide ruffle at a 7cm interval in the middle and 2cm intervals at the sides. It goes along a convex line. </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image019.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>The seams joining the ruffles look like this from the wrong side of the stiff train gore: </strong></p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image021.jpg" alt=""></p>
<p><strong>I need to put down the last top ruffle with a width of 80cm and finish the top edge of the gore. </strong>You can always trim the top ruffle if necessary.</p>
<p><strong>Please note that I had to use quite many ruffles and spend a fair amount of fabric to increase the volume of the train with the help of a stiff gore. </strong>And I am working on a mock-up skirt and not a full-size skirt, i.e. all these amounts will be double. Imagine how many ruffles you would need to give the train the same volume without adding that stiff gore piece. I believe it is very reasonable to use it for this purpose.</p>
<p><strong>Here is the ruffles layout I promised to show you.</strong> I believe you already understand how it was made. Just remember to multiply all values by two when you start working on the actual size garment.</p>
<p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Structured%20Designer%20Skirt/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image023.jpg" alt=""></p>

</div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody -->
